 entrée to an essential modern thinker.The Lily of the Field and the Bird of the Air reveals a less familiar but deeply appealing side of the father of existentialism—unshorn of his complexity and subtlety, yet supremely approachable. As Kierkegaard later wrote of the book, "Without fighting with anybody and without speaking about myself, I said much of what needs to be said, but movingly, mildly, upliftingly."This masterful edition introduces one of Kierkegaard's most engaging and inspiring works to a new generation of readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChristian lifexLutheran authors. 0aPhilosophy, Danish. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aAbsolute (philosophy).  aAllusion.  aAmericans.  aBianco Luno.  aBrief Lives.  aBuoyancy.  aCareer.  aChristendom.  aChristianity.  aClothing.  aConsider the Lilies.  aCredulity.  aDanish Golden Age.  aDiscourses (Meher Baba).  aEpicureanism.  aFigure of speech.  aGerman idealism.  aGod the Father.  aGod.  aGreek Philosophy.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aImagery.  aKingship and kingdom of God.  aLection.  aLightness (philosophy).  aLightness.  aLiterature.  aLuck.  aMeekness.  aMeteorology.  aMourning dove.  aNature.  aObedience (human behavior).  aOmnipotence.  aOven.  aPaganism.  aPhilosopher.  aPiety.  aPity.  aPopular sovereignty.  aPractice in Christianity.  aPrinting.  aPublication.  aRequirement.  aRighteousness.  aRomanticism.  aS. (Dorst novel).  aSelfishness.  aSøren Kierkegaard.  aTelegraphy.  aThe Point of View of My Work as an Author.  aThe Sickness Unto Death.  aThe gospel.  aTheodorus the Atheist.  aTheology.  aThought.  aTranscendentalism.  aUnderstanding.  aVeneration.  aWriting.1 aKirmmse, Bruce H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g